Nov 7

We now return to Lemke-Howson path following.

The idea is that given the and simplices that we've discussed, there exists some (computer programmable) method for finding a completely labeled pair which is therefore an NE.

Recall that our diagrams from before were:

In general, the procedure is as follows.

Step 1: Attach an "artificial" vertex to both the and simpliices. Call the artifical vertices and . The artifical vertex is attached to each of the three unit vector points in and respectively (which means that, in general, will be attached to unit vector points, and will be attached to unit vector points).

Note

You can also treat this as creating new regions for the outer edges.

Step 2: By perturbing lines if necessary, make sure that the simplices are in general position - that is there, are no points in with more than labels, and no points in with more than labels.

General position

The definition of being "in general position" is as follows (Shapley 111/chapter 3, p. 25):

  • Each point interior to a region has exactly one label
  • Each point interior to an edge has exactly two labels
  • Each vertex has exactly three labels

You can see this isn't fulfilled in simplex , since we have the point with four labels. We will deal with this later (and this is indeed what Quint did in class).

The significance of being in general position is the following theorem.

Remark 3.8 (Shapley 112/chapter 3, p.26)

A bimatrix game in general position has only finitely many SEs.

(Notice how our original method of finding labeled pairs gave us an entire line segment as an SE - this is because simplex is not in general position, so there were infinitely many SEs.)

Step 3: Place two "pennies" at and at . There are possible "first moves", where you move one of the pennies to an adjacent vertex.

Note

The point of the pennies is to have some region of radius that we can think of as overlapping certain regions.

One possible move is moving to the vertex labeled (1, 0, 0 in simplex ):

such that the set of labels is now

Step 4 (repeatable): Is there a completely labeled pair? If so, then we have an NE. If not, we move the "other" penny to the adjacent vertex which removes the "duplicated" label. (Implicitly, we will alternate pennies.)

So what do we have in our example? We don't have a completely labeled pair - there are two (3)s and no (A)s. So we seek to move the penny currently on vertex such that it does not "cover" include one of the edges representing (A) in simplex . In this case, we can move it to the vertex labeled (0, 0, 1 in simplex ), such that the labels are now

Again, we have no NE, so we move the other penny - currently at in simplex - such that we remove the extra (B). We move .

This gives us the labels . We now seek to eliminate the duplicate (1), so we move in simplex .


This gives us the labels . We can eliminate the duplicate (3) by creating a "perturbed" line, connecting from in simplex to a point slightly lower than , such that the penny doesn't include the region labeled (3). Call this infinitesmally lower point .

Warning

Our labels weren't 1, 2, 3, c at point E because of the "general position" condition we mentioned earlier. We only perturbed the line now, though - this is what Quint did in class.

Strictly speaking, you usually start out by perturbing the lines so that no point in the simplex has more than three labels, so that you end up with two simplices in general position. Note, of course, that this removes certain NEs.

"Perturbing" a line seems to have a fairly loose definition, but the idea is to simply "break apart" the lines. Here's a recreation of Figure 3-12 in Shapley, p. 119:

Although we've never seen the second case (and theoretically shouldn't), the first case is an example of what we could do here.

There is an important remark to note here:

Remark

In general, there are possible "first moves". But after your first move, every subsequent move has only 1 choice (that actually makes progress, assuming you make moves in alternating simplices).
